3.2 Physical Layer Synchronization: The Hydrogen Slot Clock

To enable a universal timebase, the PPM slot duration  T_s  is defined as a power‑of‑two multiple of the hyperfine transition period of neutral hydrogen:

T_H = \frac{1}{f_H} = \frac{1}{1420.40575177 \times 10^6 \text{ Hz}} \approx 0.704 \text{ ns}

Choose  T_s = 2^{10} \cdot T_H = 1024 \times 0.704 \text{ ns} \approx 720.9 \text{ ns} . The receiver first detects the hydrogen line (universally recognizable via its 21 cm wavelength), then calibrates its clock. In a photon‑starved regime, the receiver looks for a periodic “comb” in photon arrival times. By computing the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the intervals between pulses, the receiver recovers  T_s . Dividing by 1024 yields  T_H , confirming correct calibration.

3.3 Concatenated Coding for Photon‑Starved Channels

We implement SCPPM as the inner code: a convolutional code (rate 1/2, constraint length 7) followed by an accumulator, with a pseudorandom interleaver between them. The outer code is a Reed–Solomon (255,223) code, which corrects up to 16 symbol errors per codeword. This concatenated scheme has been shown to operate within 1 dB of the Shannon limit for a Mars‑distance link. NASA DSOC achieved downlink rates up to 267 Mbps at 0.37 AU using this architecture.

3.4 Self‑Bootstrapping Interleaver

The interleaver permutes the encoded bit stream across a block of size  L  (e.g.,  L = 1024  bits) before PPM modulation. Unlike a fixed random seed, the interleaver seed is derived from the first 32 bits of the handshake sequence (the Mersenne primes). This makes the system self‑bootstrapping: the handshake provides the key to unlock the interleaver, which in turn unlocks the payload. The receiver, after verifying the handshake, extracts the seed and reconstructs the de‑interleaving permutation.

