5. Encoding Architecture & Semantic Layers

5.1 Topological Primer: Adjacency Matrices and Euler Characteristic

To convey the concept of “space” without symbolic ambiguity, the ULC transmits sequences representing simplicial complexes – triangulations of simple manifolds. The data format is the adjacency matrix: a  V \times V  binary matrix where a 1 at position  (i,j)  indicates that vertices  i  and  j  are connected by an edge.

· Sphere ( S^2 ): Transmit the adjacency matrix of a tetrahedron (4 vertices, 6 edges). The receiver computes the Euler characteristic  \chi = V - E + F = 4 - 6 + 4 = 2 .
· Torus ( T^2 ): Transmit the adjacency matrix of a triangulated torus (e.g., 7 vertices, 21 edges, 14 faces). The receiver computes  \chi = 7 - 21 + 14 = 0 .

By transmitting multiple complexes and their Euler characteristics, the receiver infers the concept of genus and global topology – a purely combinatorial, base‑independent description of manifold space. The receiver can perform linear algebra on the adjacency matrix (e.g., compute its rank, eigenvalues) to verify the shape.

