the ULC sends a sequence of bitmaps:

1. Metric Tensor  g_{\mu\nu} : A  4 \times 4  grid of bits (or floating‑point approximations encoded as binary) representing the components of the metric in a chosen coordinate system.
2. Nabla Operator  \nabla : A symbolic pattern associated with the adjacency matrix’s notion of “neighbor difference” – essentially a finite‑difference stencil.
3. Einstein Tensor  G_{\mu\nu} : Derived from  g_{\mu\nu}  and its derivatives, transmitted as a bitmap after performing the algebraic operations (Riemann → Ricci → Einstein).
4. Stress‑Energy Tensor  T_{\mu\nu} : Transmitted as another  4 \times 4  bitmap.

By linking the topological primer (the shape of space) to the tensor bitmaps (how mass‑energy curves that shape), we provide a functional manual for general relativity. If the receiver can predict the motion of their own stars using our “Lingo,” the communication is successful.

5.3 Multi‑Modal Redundancy

To maximize decodability, the ULC includes multiple encoding strategies in parallel:

