Appendix A: Formal Proof of the rKt Artificiality Threshold

Problem: Distinguish a designed signal from a Natural Stochastic Process (NSP).

Definitions:

· Let  U  be a universal Turing machine with random bits. The randomized time‑bounded Kolmogorov complexity  \text{rKt}(w)  of a binary string  w  is the minimum of  |p| + \lceil \log_2 t \rceil  over all programs  p  that output  w  within  t  steps with probability  > 2/3 .
· An NSP (e.g., pulsar, quasar, thermal noise) produces strings where  \text{rKt}(w) \approx |w| . Even periodic processes have small  |w| , so the gap  |w| - \text{rKt}(w)  is bounded by a constant  C_{\text{NSP}} .

ULC Handshake:
Transmit the first  n  Mersenne primes  M_1, M_2, \dots, M_n  concatenated in binary. Because each  M_{i+1} > M_i , the sequence is self‑delimiting: the receiver can parse it by reading until the value exceeds the previous.

Complexity Analysis:

· Raw length  |w| = \sum_{i=1}^n \lfloor \log_2 M_i \rfloor + 1 \approx \sum_{i=1}^n p_i \approx \frac{1}{2} n^2 \log n  (by the prime number theorem).
· Shortest program  p : implement the sieve of Eratosthenes to generate primes  p_i , then compute  M_i = 2^{p_i} - 1 , output concatenated bits. The code size is  O(\log n)  for the loop plus a constant. The computation time  t  is dominated by the Lucas–Lehmer test for each  M_i , which runs in  O(p_i^2 \log p_i) . Hence  \log_2 t = O(\log n) .
· Therefore  \text{rKt}(w) \leq O(\log n) + O(\log n) = O(\log n) .

Artificiality Gap:

\Delta = |w| - \text{rKt}(w) \geq \frac{1}{2} n^2 \log n - O(\log n) \to \infty \quad \text{as } n \to \infty

Choose a safety margin  K = 10 . For  n  sufficiently large (e.g.,  n \geq 20 ),  \Delta > K . Since no NSP can produce such a gap, a received handshake with  \Delta > K  constitutes a mathematical proof of artificial intelligence.

